Question 6.4.3 (Smoothing of Nondifferentiables):

Function: g(lambda) = sum{u*lambda-gamma(u)}

Cost Equation: P(t) = inf {gamma(t-u)+(c/2)||u||^2}

a) Moritz Werner Fenchel, a mathematician in geometry and lecturer derived the idea:

   P(t) = inf {gamma(t-u)+(c/2)||u||^2}

   Function: gamma(t-u)
   Constraint: (c/2)||u||^2

   The horizontal shift in the dual problem is by u*lambda. 

         Function: gamma(t-u)+u*lambda + t*lambda - t*lambda = t*lambda - g(lambda)
              
         Constraint: (c/2)||u||^2-u*lambda = (1/2c)||lambda||^2

   P(t) = max{t*lambda-g(lambda)-(1/2c)||lambda||^2

b) A mini-max or max-max problem generates when gamma = max[0,t]:

     P(t) = max{t*lambda-max[0,t](t-u)+u*lambda-(1/2c)||lambda||^2}

   When gamma(t) = |t|, then:

     P(t) = max{t*lambda-|t|(t-u)+u*lambda-(1/2c)||lambda||^2}

   Also, gamma=(s/2)t*t:

     P(t) = max{t*lambda-(s/2)t*t(t-u)+u*lambda-(1/2c)||lambda||^2}

   Lastly, gamma(t) = max{t1,...,tn} is another max-max problem:

     P(t) = max{t*lambda-max[t](t-u)+u*lambda-(1/2c)||lambda||^2}

c) An analogous problem occurs when 

   P(t) = inf{gamma(t-u) + y*u + (c/2)||u||^2}

   Function: gamma(t-u) + y*u
   Constraint: (c/2)||u||^2

   The horizontal shift in a dual problem by u*lambda:
 
     Function: gamma(t-u) + y*u + u*lambda + t*lambda - t*lambda = t*lambda - g(lambda)
     Constraint: (c/2)||u||^2 - u*lambda = (1/2c)||lambda||^2

   P(t) = inf { t*lambda - g(lambda) - (1/2c)||lambda||^2}
           
